  m_Paragraphs:
    m_Items:
    - m_Type: 0
      Title:
        m_Untranslated: The Seeker Code - Setting the Desired Velocity
      Text:
        m_Untranslated: "This next part within <c>FixedUpdate</c> is the code-version
          of the diagrams we saw earlier. Unity's <doc>Vector2</doc> class makes
          it easy to work with vectors/directions.\nAs mentioned before, the job
          of our AI classes is to set a <c>desiredVelocity</c>, and the <asset>Mover</asset>
          will work out the rest!\n<code>\nvar separationVector = target.transform.position
          - transform.position;\ndesiredVelocity = separationVector.normalized *
          speed;\n</code>\nThe code calculates a <b>separation vector</b> (i.e. the
          vector between two points) between the target and the player. Instead of
          using this vector directly as the velocity, we first <b>normalize</b> it
          (resize the arrow so it has a constant length of <b>1</b>). \nWithout normalizing
          the vector, the enemy would move faster toward the player when it is further
          away as the magnitude of the separation vector is larger. A larger magnitude
          on a velocity means a faster speed. \nThe <c>desiredVelocity</c> is multiplied
          by this object\u2019s <c>speed</c> multiplier. \nNote, we don't put <c>var</c>
          in front of <c>desiredVelocity</c> because that variable is already defined
          -- <i>in the parent class</i><asset>Mover</asset> (on line 21).\n<c>speed</c>
          is also defined in <asset>Mover</asset> on line 12."
